<dl id="n53046b"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n53" href="#n53046b">N53 (VI.B.46)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n53all.htm#n53046b"> 46(b)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> hyacinth = / heliotrope <small>Red</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n53046b"><li>FW 603.28 </li><li><a href="../../flex/ta/lexta.htm#n53046b">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/ta/l39ta.htm#n53046b">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n53046b">MS BL 47488-35v</ms> </li><li>JJA 63:058 <a name="tad3" href="../../ff/fdra/tda.htm#tad3">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/ta/tad3.htm#n53046b">Draft: IV&sect;1.3</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources"><font color="green">[The native way of ancient story-telling has indeed been overcome. An extreme example of such unscientific thinking is the Greek legend of the <mark>hyacinth&apos;s</mark> genesis &hellip; The sun god of the Hyakinth festival was associated personally with the flower.]</font> <small> Fritz Mauthner, <a name="FMBK1" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#FMBK1"><cite title="source">Beitr&auml;ge zu einer Kritik der Sprache.</cite></a> 3 vols (1901-2) III 502</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: Turquoise ink. <br>Hyacinthus, in Greek mythology, was loved by Apollo. Zephyrus &mdash; inflamed with jealousy &mdash; directed Apollo&apos;s quoit at the boy&apos;s head, killing him. From the blood thus spilled sprang the hyacinth flower. Klyt&apos;ie was a nymph who died of grief upon being forsaken by Apollo. She was immortalised as the heliotrope flower.] </mm> </dd></dl>
